Notes_Migration: BOW notes that this species is mainly sedentary, with partial migration in northern populations; overall, migration is poorly understood. This species is now classified as the American goshawk (Accipiter atricapillus). Accipiter gentilis is the Eurasian goshawk. These species recently underwent review and reclassification by the American Ornithological Society based on new genetic evidence -- they were once considered the same species but are now considered separate.

Population_1: Yukon Harbor, Big Koniuji Island, Alaska, USA
Notes: Stresscort presented but pooled across sexes; incubation and early chick rearing
Notes_Migration: Very little is known about migration. Some individuals must migrate because they breed in areas that are covered with ice in the winter. However, crested auklets are found yearround in this location, so this population is listed as "unknown" for both Migratory_Status and Mixed_Status_Species. Some studies in Buldir, Alaska indicate the species is migratory, but the sample sizes are small and these studies were conducted at a different location.

Whelan et al. (2020) tracked birds from this colony at Middleton Island and found that some migrated and some did not (partial migration). Marking Migratory_Status as Unknown.
